1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:00,830
Speaker 3: Hi, everyone.

2
00:00:01,240 --> 00:00:02,959
My name is Andrei Shcherbinin.

3
00:00:03,110 --> 00:00:07,840
I'm a machine learning team
leader at Social Discovery Group.

4
00:00:08,330 --> 00:00:12,920
Today, I'll talk about building a
machine learning auto moderation system

5
00:00:12,930 --> 00:00:15,409
for LLM-augmented online platforms.

6
00:00:16,270 --> 00:00:18,819
The main idea of this
talk is really simple.

7
00:00:18,919 --> 00:00:24,310
Moderation is no longer just about
detecting bad words in user messages.

8
00:00:25,249 --> 00:00:28,700
Moderation platforms deal
with human-written messages,

9
00:00:28,749 --> 00:00:34,039
AI-assisted content, and in some
cases, even agentic interactions.

10
00:00:34,539 --> 00:00:39,039
So the question becomes, how do we
build a moderation system that is safe,

11
00:00:39,039 --> 00:00:43,869
scalable, cost-efficient, and still
flexible enough to handle gray zones?

12
00:00:44,689 --> 00:00:52,699
I will walk through the full system, from
policy design to hybrid model architecture

13
00:00:53,699 --> 00:00:55,789
and monitoring the whole system.

14
00:00:56,289 --> 00:00:59,189
The goal is not to show one magic model.

15
00:00:59,409 --> 00:01:04,099
The goal is to show how moderation
works in a production ML system

16
00:01:04,599 --> 00:01:08,309
When people hear auto-moderation,
they often imagine a classifier

17
00:01:08,809 --> 00:01:13,369
that receives a message and returns
something like safe or unsafe.

18
00:01:13,759 --> 00:01:17,799
But it's a real product,
especially in a dating platform.

19
00:01:18,459 --> 00:01:21,119
This is only a small part of the story.

20
00:01:21,979 --> 00:01:26,319
A production moderation system has to
answer several questions at the same time.

21
00:01:26,949 --> 00:01:28,639
Is this message a violation?

22
00:01:28,699 --> 00:01:29,989
How confident we are?

23
00:01:30,669 --> 00:01:32,419
How severe is the risk?

24
00:01:32,859 --> 00:01:38,109
Should we block it immediately or send
it to a reviewer, lower its priority,

25
00:01:38,149 --> 00:01:39,839
or just lock it for monitoring?

26
00:01:40,659 --> 00:01:44,379
And what happens when user
behavior changes next week?

27
00:01:45,259 --> 00:01:50,259
This presentation, I'll focus on the
engineering side of moderation, how

28
00:01:50,259 --> 00:01:54,659
we move from raw production messages
to policy-aligned labels, then to

29
00:01:54,659 --> 00:01:59,029
models, thresholds, reviewer queues,
monitoring, and continuous retraining.

30
00:01:59,669 --> 00:02:04,689
The key message is LLM-powered
moderation works best when it's designed

31
00:02:04,799 --> 00:02:06,989
as a system, not as a single model.

32
00:02:07,489 --> 00:02:13,549
This slide shows why moderation changes
when platform become LLM-augmented.

33
00:02:14,049 --> 00:02:18,429
On the classic platform, we mostly
moderate human-written messages.

34
00:02:18,529 --> 00:02:23,419
Abuse patterns are often repeated:
links, spam templates, obvious

35
00:02:23,429 --> 00:02:25,379
harassment, simple obfuscation.

36
00:02:25,579 --> 00:02:30,449
Rules and keyword filters can
catch a meaningful part of this.

37
00:02:31,099 --> 00:02:37,119
But when LLMs enter the system, the same
intent can appear in many more forms.

38
00:02:37,959 --> 00:02:42,389
The content becomes more diverse,
more fluent, and more paraphrased.

39
00:02:42,889 --> 00:02:46,659
A scammer no longer needs to
copy-paste the same message.

40
00:02:46,939 --> 00:02:51,069
They can generate a hundred polite
variations of the same manipulation.

41
00:02:51,619 --> 00:02:54,999
And the next stage is even more
interesting, agentic platforms.

42
00:02:55,009 --> 00:03:00,399
Here, AI is not only writing text, but
may help perform actions, summarize,

43
00:03:00,459 --> 00:03:05,839
browse, generate images, contact users,
or assist with multi-step workflows.

44
00:03:06,339 --> 00:03:09,999
At that point, moderation is no
longer just text classification.

45
00:03:10,179 --> 00:03:16,079
It becomes risk assessment over text,
context, tools, and possible actions.

46
00:03:16,579 --> 00:03:20,339
Old school spam was at least
polite enough to repeat itself.

47
00:03:20,459 --> 00:03:24,569
LLM-assisted abuse is more creative,
which is very inconvenient for us.

48
00:03:25,139 --> 00:03:31,409
So the core shift is this: LLM don't
only increase the amount of content,

49
00:03:31,559 --> 00:03:37,459
they change the shape of abuse, and
that requires a moderation system that

50
00:03:37,549 --> 00:03:44,199
understands context, not just surface
patterns Now let's talk about why this

51
00:03:44,199 --> 00:03:46,489
matters specifically for dating platforms.

52
00:03:47,149 --> 00:03:51,289
In dating, safety is not
a back-office function.

53
00:03:51,839 --> 00:03:54,459
It's a part of the
product experience itself.

54
00:03:55,029 --> 00:04:01,389
Users come to the platform to communicate,
build trust, and often share private

55
00:04:01,449 --> 00:04:03,509
or emotionally vulnerable content.

56
00:04:04,329 --> 00:04:09,969
If they feel unsafe, the product fails,
even if all technical metrics looks fine.

57
00:04:10,719 --> 00:04:12,639
There are three dimensions here.

58
00:04:13,189 --> 00:04:15,939
The first is emotional trust.

59
00:04:16,359 --> 00:04:20,889
Users need to believe that the person
on the other side is real respectful

60
00:04:20,929 --> 00:04:22,709
and not trying to exploit them.

61
00:04:23,189 --> 00:04:25,739
The second is financial risk.

62
00:04:25,859 --> 00:04:31,659
Dating platforms are a natural
target for romance fraud, scam,

63
00:04:31,679 --> 00:04:37,359
payment manipulations, and attempts
to move conversations off-platform.

64
00:04:37,949 --> 00:04:41,609
The third platform-- The
third is the platform health.

65
00:04:42,299 --> 00:04:46,389
Bad actors increase support
load, damage conversions, reduce

66
00:04:46,389 --> 00:04:48,219
retention, and harm the brand.

67
00:04:48,719 --> 00:04:54,209
This is why I like the phrase
on the slide, "Moderation is

68
00:04:54,709 --> 00:04:56,145
part of core product quality." In some
products, bad content is inconvenience.

69
00:04:56,145 --> 00:05:00,685
In dating, it become the central
reason why users leave And the

70
00:05:00,695 --> 00:05:02,705
hardest cases are not always obvious.

71
00:05:03,045 --> 00:05:06,575
Manipulation, grooming-like
behavior, coded language, and

72
00:05:06,785 --> 00:05:11,315
indirect harassment often look
harmless in one isolated message.

73
00:05:11,775 --> 00:05:17,475
This is why the system has to
combine ML, LLM reasoning, human

74
00:05:17,475 --> 00:05:19,805
judgment, and product context.

75
00:05:20,305 --> 00:05:23,765
Moderation is not a normal
classification problem.

76
00:05:24,265 --> 00:05:27,665
In many categories, violations are rare.

77
00:05:27,995 --> 00:05:29,805
The majority of messages are normal.

78
00:05:30,805 --> 00:05:32,895
This creates a strong class imbalance.

79
00:05:33,495 --> 00:05:37,185
If you optimize for accuracy,
you can get a very good-looking

80
00:05:37,185 --> 00:05:39,815
number or by doing almost nothing.

81
00:05:40,435 --> 00:05:45,985
For example, if only one percent of
messages are violations, a model that

82
00:05:45,985 --> 00:05:51,035
predicts normal for everything can
already look ninety-nine percent accurate.

83
00:05:51,665 --> 00:05:55,485
It's actually useless, but it
looks great on a dashboard.

84
00:05:55,805 --> 00:05:58,475
This is the kind of magic that
makes everyone happy until

85
00:05:58,475 --> 00:06:00,485
production starts burning.

86
00:06:01,035 --> 00:06:04,105
The real problem is the cost of mistakes.

87
00:06:04,725 --> 00:06:08,775
A false positive means we
wrongly affect a normal user.

88
00:06:09,175 --> 00:06:13,945
Maybe we hide a message, block an
account, or send something harmless to

89
00:06:13,945 --> 00:06:17,145
review that creates product friction.

90
00:06:17,645 --> 00:06:22,265
A false negative means we miss a
harmful message that creates safety

91
00:06:22,265 --> 00:06:26,405
exposure, and depending on the category,
the cost can be very different.

92
00:06:26,905 --> 00:06:32,215
Missing mild toxicity is not the same as
missing grooming-like behavior or scam.

93
00:06:32,715 --> 00:06:36,485
So the goal is not accuracy,
the goal is controlled risk.

94
00:06:36,695 --> 00:06:41,685
We need category-specific thresholds,
severity-aware evaluation, and good

95
00:06:41,705 --> 00:06:44,325
understanding of reviewer capacity.

96
00:06:45,285 --> 00:06:50,685
This is why precision, recall, Q quality,
and false positive analysis matter much

97
00:06:50,685 --> 00:06:53,205
more than one global offline score.

98
00:06:53,705 --> 00:06:58,815
In moderation, policy is not just
documentation around the model.

99
00:06:59,755 --> 00:07:02,275
Policy is part of the model specification.

100
00:07:02,375 --> 00:07:06,295
Model cannot learn bad
behavior in the abstract.

101
00:07:06,385 --> 00:07:10,765
It learns a specific taxonomy,
specific labels, specific definitions,

102
00:07:11,405 --> 00:07:13,505
and specific decision rules.

103
00:07:13,765 --> 00:07:19,165
So if the policy is vague, inconsistent,
or not mapped into ML terms, the

104
00:07:19,175 --> 00:07:21,535
model will inherit that ambiguity.

105
00:07:22,035 --> 00:07:28,835
The table shows how policy objects map
into ML objects and production objects.

106
00:07:29,355 --> 00:07:31,835
Evaluation time becomes a category label.

107
00:07:32,135 --> 00:07:33,835
Severity becomes a risk score.

108
00:07:33,955 --> 00:07:37,145
Confidence becomes a
probability or threshold.

109
00:07:37,715 --> 00:07:41,125
Context becomes features
or prompt information.

110
00:07:41,265 --> 00:07:45,795
Reviewer decisions become corrected
labels and retraining data.

111
00:07:46,645 --> 00:07:51,465
This means that policy design, labeling
instructions, and production routing

112
00:07:51,505 --> 00:07:53,255
are not separate from machine learning.

113
00:07:53,665 --> 00:07:55,805
They are part of the ML system.

114
00:07:56,665 --> 00:08:01,785
For example, suspicious of platform
behavior is not enough as a label.

115
00:08:02,135 --> 00:08:06,705
We need to define what exactly counts:
direct contact exchange, payment

116
00:08:06,705 --> 00:08:11,955
redirection, external messenger
invitation, manipulation, urgency,

117
00:08:12,045 --> 00:08:14,695
or only some combination of this.

118
00:08:15,445 --> 00:08:20,805
The better the policy definition,
the easier is to label data,

119
00:08:20,845 --> 00:08:24,235
train models, calibrate
thresholds, and explain decisions.

120
00:08:24,995 --> 00:08:29,505
So before we ask which model should
we use, we should ask what exactly

121
00:08:29,575 --> 00:08:31,965
are we asking t-the model to learn?

122
00:08:32,465 --> 00:08:38,275
The main point of this slide is that
auto moderation is an operating system

123
00:08:38,285 --> 00:08:41,815
for safety decision, not one classifier.

124
00:08:42,475 --> 00:08:47,075
We start with rule charts Then we
clean the data, de-duplicate it.

125
00:08:47,385 --> 00:08:54,395
Sample examples, use LLM labeling,
validate with humans, train models, run

126
00:08:54,455 --> 00:09:01,815
online inference, apply thresholds, route
cases to review queues, and finally,

127
00:09:01,875 --> 00:09:04,595
use feedback for the next iteration.

128
00:09:05,095 --> 00:09:09,615
The arrows at the bottom are just
as important as the main pipeline.

129
00:09:09,715 --> 00:09:16,035
Reviewers' decisions go back into sampling
prompts, thresholds, and retraining.

130
00:09:16,415 --> 00:09:20,275
Monitoring also feeds
back into the system.

131
00:09:20,775 --> 00:09:23,625
This is important because
abuse is not static.

132
00:09:24,245 --> 00:09:28,495
If we build a one-time
classifier and never re-revisit

133
00:09:28,495 --> 00:09:30,155
it, performance will degrade.

134
00:09:30,665 --> 00:09:35,445
Users change wording, scammers
test boundaries, product

135
00:09:35,445 --> 00:09:38,915
surfaces change, policies change.

136
00:09:39,435 --> 00:09:43,515
Even the meaning of the bottom
line case can shift over time.

137
00:09:44,015 --> 00:09:48,975
A useful way to think about it is
the model is not only one component.

138
00:09:49,055 --> 00:09:52,425
The system includes data
engineering, policy mapping,

139
00:09:52,525 --> 00:09:57,495
annotation tools, review operations,
dashboards, and retraining loops.

140
00:09:58,075 --> 00:10:02,595
So when someone say, "Can we just
use a strong LLM for moderation?"

141
00:10:02,785 --> 00:10:07,315
The answer is maybe for one layer,
but not for the whole system.

142
00:10:07,445 --> 00:10:12,465
The whole system is where moderation
quality actually comes from

143
00:10:12,965 --> 00:10:14,955
Now let's zoom into the data layer.

144
00:10:15,135 --> 00:10:17,855
Raw messages are not just training data.

145
00:10:18,015 --> 00:10:23,625
They become training data only after they
are cleaned, filtered, aligned the policy,

146
00:10:23,685 --> 00:10:25,545
and connected to the right context.

147
00:10:26,355 --> 00:10:31,565
On the left side of the slide, we have
sources: user-to-user messages, user

148
00:10:31,565 --> 00:10:36,845
reports, reviewer decisions, metadata,
and historical moderation actions.

149
00:10:37,325 --> 00:10:38,935
The middle part is alignment.

150
00:10:39,485 --> 00:10:42,435
We remove test traffic and obvious noise.

151
00:10:42,505 --> 00:10:44,925
We map examples to policy categories.

152
00:10:45,035 --> 00:10:47,425
We preserve user type and context.

153
00:10:48,005 --> 00:10:52,525
We split by language, product, and
platform because behavior can be

154
00:10:52,645 --> 00:10:54,125
very different across segments.

155
00:10:55,125 --> 00:11:00,585
On the right side, we can get the
output, a clean candidate corpus,

156
00:11:00,645 --> 00:11:04,355
policy-aware samples, and rare
class candidates for labeling.

157
00:11:05,095 --> 00:11:09,015
This step is less glamorous than
model training, but it defines

158
00:11:09,035 --> 00:11:11,515
a ceiling of model qua- quality.

159
00:11:12,495 --> 00:11:18,905
If the data is noisy, duplicated, stale,
or poorly aligned with policy, even a very

160
00:11:18,905 --> 00:11:21,315
strong model will learn the wrong thing.

161
00:11:21,815 --> 00:11:25,105
In dating platforms, context
is especially important.

162
00:11:25,175 --> 00:11:29,175
The same phrase can have different
meaning depending on who sends it, how

163
00:11:29,175 --> 00:11:31,285
often it appears, what happened before.

164
00:11:31,925 --> 00:11:35,335
So data collection is not
just give me all messages.

165
00:11:35,445 --> 00:11:39,255
It is the first safety decision design

166
00:11:39,755 --> 00:11:42,855
Without deduplication, the
model often learns templates

167
00:11:42,865 --> 00:11:44,695
instead of abuse semantics.

168
00:11:44,805 --> 00:11:47,695
This is a very common
trap in moderation data.

169
00:11:48,325 --> 00:11:52,175
Models may learn bad signals.

170
00:11:52,675 --> 00:11:56,055
Imagine we have thousands of
near-identical scam messages.

171
00:11:56,135 --> 00:11:58,855
Hey, babe, help me with my phone bill.

172
00:11:58,925 --> 00:12:01,215
Hi, dear, I need help with my bill.

173
00:12:01,825 --> 00:12:03,265
Can you send me money to help me?

174
00:12:03,765 --> 00:12:08,245
The model may become very good at
recognizing these exact templates, and

175
00:12:08,245 --> 00:12:10,435
then we celebrate high offline quality.

176
00:12:10,745 --> 00:12:15,255
But in production, when the
wording changes, the model fails.

177
00:12:15,785 --> 00:12:21,085
So deduplication is not only
compression, it is evaluation hygiene.

178
00:12:21,435 --> 00:12:25,525
It reduces memorization,
reduces train test leakage, and

179
00:12:25,525 --> 00:12:27,635
helps us preserve diversity.

180
00:12:28,225 --> 00:12:30,655
The goal is not to remove
everything similar.

181
00:12:30,885 --> 00:12:34,575
The goal is to collapse
repetitive templates while

182
00:12:34,585 --> 00:12:37,135
keeping representative variations.

183
00:12:37,635 --> 00:12:42,195
In our pipeline, this means
exact deduplication, normalized

184
00:12:42,195 --> 00:12:46,045
deduplication, and then broader
methods for near duplicates.

185
00:12:46,525 --> 00:12:49,655
For wider semantic clusters,
we need to be careful.

186
00:12:50,075 --> 00:12:54,235
If we merge too aggressively,
we lose meaningful diversity.

187
00:12:55,225 --> 00:12:59,255
If we merge too weakly, the
dataset stays full of templates.

188
00:12:59,755 --> 00:13:03,915
If you train on the same scam
template ten thousand times, you

189
00:13:03,935 --> 00:13:05,725
have not built a moderation model.

190
00:13:06,275 --> 00:13:11,635
You have built a very expensive
template historian The key idea here

191
00:13:11,635 --> 00:13:15,865
is that for rare violations progress
should be measured by positives

192
00:13:15,875 --> 00:13:17,725
found, not by rows processed.

193
00:13:18,225 --> 00:13:22,095
If the positive class is around
one percent, then random labeling

194
00:13:22,165 --> 00:13:23,505
is extremely inefficient.

195
00:13:23,905 --> 00:13:28,935
Most of the labeling budget is
spent confirming normal messages.

196
00:13:29,515 --> 00:13:34,975
That may be useful at some point, but
it's not the fastest way to build a

197
00:13:35,215 --> 00:13:37,675
training set for a rare violation.

198
00:13:38,175 --> 00:13:40,775
So the pipeline works like this.

199
00:13:41,405 --> 00:13:44,005
We sample a batch, we remove
texts that were already

200
00:13:44,005 --> 00:13:45,905
evaluated using a hash journal.

201
00:13:46,215 --> 00:13:54,445
We retrieve few-shot examples from golden
set, then the LLM classifies each message.

202
00:13:55,095 --> 00:13:59,595
The label can be zero for clear
normal, one for cla-clear violation,

203
00:13:59,895 --> 00:14:03,625
or two for borderline, meaning the
ca-the case should be reviewed.

204
00:14:04,125 --> 00:14:07,235
This is a very practical
engineering principle.

205
00:14:07,305 --> 00:14:12,055
We don't want to label everything,
we want to find enough signal.

206
00:14:12,575 --> 00:14:15,965
The hash journal is important
because labeling is expensive.

207
00:14:16,025 --> 00:14:19,375
We don't want to pay repeatedly
for the same text across

208
00:14:19,725 --> 00:14:21,735
restarts or dataset updates.

209
00:14:22,315 --> 00:14:27,655
Few-shot retrieval is also important
because the system improves over time.

210
00:14:28,015 --> 00:14:34,065
As humans validate examples, those
examples become better context for

211
00:14:34,315 --> 00:14:36,115
the next LLM labeling iteration

212
00:14:36,615 --> 00:14:39,495
LLMs are extremely useful
for pre-annotation.

213
00:14:39,645 --> 00:14:44,755
They can read text, produce a label,
explain the reason, and highlight the

214
00:14:44,755 --> 00:14:46,815
fragment that supports the decision.

215
00:14:47,315 --> 00:14:52,215
This reduces the cognitive load for the
human reviewer, but we should not train

216
00:14:52,225 --> 00:14:57,685
the final production model directly
on raw LLM labels without validation.

217
00:14:58,185 --> 00:15:02,605
If we do that, the model
may learn the LLM's mistakes

218
00:15:02,875 --> 00:15:04,655
instead of the actual policy.

219
00:15:05,155 --> 00:15:11,925
So the human-in-the-loop process works
like this: The LLM gives a suggestion,

220
00:15:12,675 --> 00:15:15,505
a reason, and a supporting fragment.

221
00:15:16,135 --> 00:15:18,635
The human accepts or rejects it.

222
00:15:18,825 --> 00:15:21,735
The validated result
goes into the golden set.

223
00:15:22,485 --> 00:15:27,055
The golden set then becomes training data
for the production model and also improves

224
00:15:27,065 --> 00:15:29,065
few-shot retrieval for future labeling.

225
00:15:29,975 --> 00:15:33,805
I like to describe the LLM here
as a very confident intern.

226
00:15:33,885 --> 00:15:38,035
It's fast, useful, and often
right, but you still don't let the

227
00:15:38,065 --> 00:15:40,745
intern define company policy alone.

228
00:15:41,245 --> 00:15:45,725
So the rule is: LLM pre-annotates,
human validates, and the

229
00:15:45,725 --> 00:15:48,295
golden set belongs to humans.

230
00:15:48,795 --> 00:15:53,205
S-- thi-this slide, I would like
to tell you about gray zones.

231
00:15:53,425 --> 00:15:59,235
The hardest violations often don't look
like violations in one isolated message.

232
00:15:59,735 --> 00:16:03,965
They emerge from context,
repetition, coded language, or the

233
00:16:04,035 --> 00:16:06,045
relationships between messages.

234
00:16:06,545 --> 00:16:12,265
Examples include grooming-like behavior,
indirect harassment, or platform

235
00:16:12,265 --> 00:16:18,745
manipulations scam, and romantic
fraud a generic moderation model may

236
00:16:18,795 --> 00:16:21,125
perform well on obvious toxicity.

237
00:16:21,585 --> 00:16:27,755
For example, direct insult or explicit
threats are easier, but dating safety

238
00:16:28,255 --> 00:16:33,365
often depends on subtle signals,
trust-building, emotional pressure,

239
00:16:33,575 --> 00:16:38,235
urgency, requests to move to another
platform, financial manipulation,

240
00:16:38,315 --> 00:16:40,775
or repeated boundary pushing.

241
00:16:41,635 --> 00:16:43,805
This is where
context-dependent risk appears.

242
00:16:44,095 --> 00:16:45,855
One message might look harmless.

243
00:16:45,915 --> 00:16:49,015
Ten messages in sequence
might show a clear pattern.

244
00:16:49,515 --> 00:16:52,625
This is why gray zones
require a hybrid approach.

245
00:16:52,835 --> 00:16:55,405
Rules can catch obvious cases.

246
00:16:55,505 --> 00:16:58,605
Lightweight models can handle
high-volume categories.

247
00:16:58,715 --> 00:17:04,375
LLM can help reason over nuanced
cases, and humans should remain

248
00:17:04,715 --> 00:17:08,875
the final authority for the
most sensitive decisions.

249
00:17:09,755 --> 00:17:14,695
So the purpose of the LLM layer
is not to replace all moderation,

250
00:17:14,765 --> 00:17:20,035
it's to help identify and explain
context-dependent risk A hybrid stack

251
00:17:20,185 --> 00:17:22,845
wins because harms differ structurally.

252
00:17:23,205 --> 00:17:26,435
At the bottom, we have rules and keywords.

253
00:17:26,625 --> 00:17:28,645
They are fast, cheap, and explainable.

254
00:17:29,025 --> 00:17:31,945
They are good for links,
obvious abuse, obfuscation, and

255
00:17:32,025 --> 00:17:33,425
deterministic policy checks.

256
00:17:33,835 --> 00:17:37,495
Their weaknesses is
that they miss context.

257
00:17:37,575 --> 00:17:40,075
Then we have lightweight machine learning.

258
00:17:40,595 --> 00:17:46,525
This is useful for high volume categories
where we need scalable online inference.

259
00:17:46,785 --> 00:17:51,085
These models are much cheaper and
faster than large LLMs, but they need

260
00:17:51,085 --> 00:17:52,835
strong labels and good evaluation.

261
00:17:53,635 --> 00:17:57,345
Then we have LLM or LLM judges.

262
00:17:57,805 --> 00:18:02,495
They are useful for gray zones, reasoning,
context, and more nuanced cases.

263
00:18:02,855 --> 00:18:05,625
But they are more expensive
and slower, so we should not

264
00:18:05,625 --> 00:18:07,815
use them everywhere by default.

265
00:18:08,295 --> 00:18:11,755
And at the top, we have a human review.

266
00:18:12,345 --> 00:18:17,305
Humans are the policy authority,
especially for edge cases, appeals,

267
00:18:17,405 --> 00:18:19,315
and high severity categories.

268
00:18:20,075 --> 00:18:21,565
But human capacity is limited.

269
00:18:22,065 --> 00:18:26,295
The important point is that the
stack is not a competition between

270
00:18:26,295 --> 00:18:29,235
rules, ML, LLMs, and humans.

271
00:18:29,635 --> 00:18:31,555
It's a division of labor.

272
00:18:32,055 --> 00:18:35,885
Today, BERT-like and other
lightweight classifiers are still

273
00:18:35,885 --> 00:18:38,005
very practical for online moderation.

274
00:18:38,325 --> 00:18:41,535
They are fast, predictable,
rela- relatively cheap, and

275
00:18:41,605 --> 00:18:43,515
easy to deploy at high volume.

276
00:18:43,995 --> 00:18:47,165
But I think the direction is really clear.

277
00:18:47,495 --> 00:18:52,255
LLMs are becoming faster, cheaper,
and stronger at reasoning.

278
00:18:52,355 --> 00:18:56,865
So over time, more moderation tasks
will naturally move from classic

279
00:18:56,865 --> 00:19:01,985
lightweight classifiers towards
specialized LLM-based moderation layers.

280
00:19:02,745 --> 00:19:07,395
This doesn't mean that rules or
small models will disappear tomorrow.

281
00:19:07,695 --> 00:19:10,735
For obvious cases, deterministic
checks and lightweight

282
00:19:10,735 --> 00:19:13,755
models will still make sense.

283
00:19:14,255 --> 00:19:19,445
But for tasks where context, nuance,
explanation, or policy reasoning

284
00:19:19,455 --> 00:19:21,955
matter, LLMs are much better fit.

285
00:19:22,645 --> 00:19:26,675
So this hybrid architecture is not
only a current production design,

286
00:19:27,215 --> 00:19:29,025
it’s also a transition path.

287
00:19:29,485 --> 00:19:34,185
We can use lightweight models where speed
and cost matter most, and gradually move

288
00:19:34,325 --> 00:19:40,355
more complex reasoning-heavy moderation
tasks to LLMs as the technology becomes

289
00:19:40,355 --> 00:19:42,465
cheaper and more production ready.

290
00:19:42,965 --> 00:19:48,445
Not every moderation tasks requires
expensive LLM inference, but

291
00:19:48,445 --> 00:19:53,365
not every moderation task can be
solved by a regex or a BERT either.

292
00:19:54,285 --> 00:19:59,715
The system works when each layer
handles the type of risk it's best

293
00:19:59,715 --> 00:20:04,915
suited for The model score is not
the final moderation decision.

294
00:20:05,015 --> 00:20:07,345
It's only one input.

295
00:20:07,615 --> 00:20:11,135
In production, a message
goes through risk signals.

296
00:20:11,925 --> 00:20:16,255
These signals can include model
probability, category, severity, user

297
00:20:16,255 --> 00:20:20,125
risk, conversation context, language.

298
00:20:20,625 --> 00:20:23,455
Then the decision layer chooses an action.

299
00:20:23,735 --> 00:20:29,025
The action can be allow, review,
priority review, block, or escalate.

300
00:20:29,565 --> 00:20:33,395
This is where moderation
becomes product engineering.

301
00:20:33,895 --> 00:20:38,045
For example, the same model
score may lead to different

302
00:20:38,135 --> 00:20:41,095
actions depending on severity.

303
00:20:41,105 --> 00:20:45,715
A medium confidence spam case
may go to a low priority review

304
00:20:45,755 --> 00:20:48,555
queue or be automatically handled.

305
00:20:48,705 --> 00:20:53,855
A medium confidence grooming-like case
may require escalation because the

306
00:20:53,855 --> 00:20:56,635
cost of missing it is much higher.

307
00:20:57,135 --> 00:20:59,995
Review, reviewer capacity also matters.

308
00:21:00,555 --> 00:21:04,985
If the review queue is overloaded,
thresholds and prioritization

309
00:21:05,285 --> 00:21:07,225
become operational controls.

310
00:21:07,575 --> 00:21:11,295
We need to decide which cases
deserve attention first.

311
00:21:11,795 --> 00:21:17,935
This is why moderation system cannot stop
at model predicted zero point eighty-two.

312
00:21:18,465 --> 00:21:23,485
The system must define what this number
means for this category, this user, this

313
00:21:23,985 --> 00:21:26,295
context, and this operational state.

314
00:21:26,865 --> 00:21:31,625
So the phrase describes my message.

315
00:21:31,695 --> 00:21:34,855
Prediction is machine learning.

316
00:21:35,425 --> 00:21:41,355
Decisioning is product engineering
Thresholds are operational controls,

317
00:21:41,425 --> 00:21:44,015
not fixed machine learning constants.

318
00:21:44,325 --> 00:21:48,445
On the slide, we have a score
distribution from zero to one.

319
00:21:48,945 --> 00:21:50,715
Low scores go to allow.

320
00:21:51,065 --> 00:21:52,705
Medium scores go to review.

321
00:21:53,065 --> 00:21:55,865
High scores go to block or urgent review.

322
00:21:56,375 --> 00:22:02,255
This looks simple, but the important
part of the threshold should be

323
00:22:02,755 --> 00:22:05,505
category specific and risk specific.

324
00:22:05,685 --> 00:22:10,205
For spam, we may want higher
autom-automation because the category

325
00:22:10,465 --> 00:22:15,045
is less vigorous and the cost of
false positive may be manageable.

326
00:22:15,725 --> 00:22:21,315
For harassment, the decision may be more
review heavy because context matters.

327
00:22:21,815 --> 00:22:27,205
A common mistake is to search for the best
thresholds once and then forget about it.

328
00:22:27,925 --> 00:22:33,335
Unfortunately, thresholds are not
a Wi-Fi password that you write

329
00:22:33,335 --> 00:22:34,775
on a stick and never update.

330
00:22:35,135 --> 00:22:40,555
Thresholds need re-recalibration when
policy changes, when the abuse mix

331
00:22:40,555 --> 00:22:46,115
changes, when a model is updated,
or when review capacity changes.

332
00:22:46,645 --> 00:22:50,695
So thresholding is not just
model tuning, it's an ongoing

333
00:22:50,745 --> 00:22:52,385
operational process for us.

334
00:22:52,885 --> 00:22:55,925
Offline metrics, of course,
important, but they are not

335
00:22:56,075 --> 00:22:57,655
enough for moderation quality.

336
00:22:58,155 --> 00:23:05,295
On the left, we have metrics such as
precision at low recall, recall on high

337
00:23:05,295 --> 00:23:12,085
severity classes, false positive rate
by category, Q precision and others.

338
00:23:12,455 --> 00:23:16,695
These metrics reflect the
reality of moderation better

339
00:23:16,695 --> 00:23:18,835
than one global F1 score.

340
00:23:19,325 --> 00:23:21,735
The loop on the right
shows how system improves.

341
00:23:22,235 --> 00:23:27,025
First, the model makes predictions,
scores, categories, or risk signals.

342
00:23:27,405 --> 00:23:33,285
The reviewers make decisions and provide
human labels rational and actions.

343
00:23:33,785 --> 00:23:37,715
Then we analyze error buckets,
false positive, false negative,

344
00:23:37,755 --> 00:23:40,535
disagreement, borderline cases, and drift

345
00:23:41,035 --> 00:23:44,915
After that, we can improve
different parts of the system.

346
00:23:44,965 --> 00:23:47,965
Sometimes the policy needs clarification.

347
00:23:47,975 --> 00:23:52,605
Sometimes the prompt needs
better instructions or examples.

348
00:23:52,785 --> 00:23:56,305
Sometimes the thresholds
needs calibration.

349
00:23:56,805 --> 00:23:59,625
Sometimes we need to
retrain with new hard cases.

350
00:24:00,225 --> 00:24:05,295
The important and the idea of that
disagreement is not only noise.

351
00:24:05,755 --> 00:24:10,805
In subjective and high-risk
tasks, disagreement is signal.

352
00:24:11,155 --> 00:24:17,075
It tells us where the policy is
unclear, where the model lacks context.

353
00:24:17,475 --> 00:24:24,095
So evaluation is not a final exam,
it's a continuous diagnostic system

354
00:24:24,595 --> 00:24:29,765
A moderation model should be rolled
out like a safety critical system The

355
00:24:29,825 --> 00:24:32,595
timeline starts with offline validation.

356
00:24:32,745 --> 00:24:36,655
Then we use shadow mode when
the model makes predictions

357
00:24:36,665 --> 00:24:38,215
but does not affect users.

358
00:24:38,255 --> 00:24:42,965
This allows us to compare model
decision with existing processes.

359
00:24:43,465 --> 00:24:48,075
The bottom part of the slide shows
that we need to monitor traffic volume,

360
00:24:48,105 --> 00:24:55,455
category distribution, review load,
backlog, SLA, latency, error, drift.

361
00:24:56,065 --> 00:24:58,845
Production ML often fails silently.

362
00:24:59,185 --> 00:25:00,955
It doesn't always crash.

363
00:25:00,955 --> 00:25:06,705
Sometimes the service is healthy,
latency is fine, error rate is

364
00:25:06,705 --> 00:25:10,385
zero, and the model is simply
making worse decisions than before.

365
00:25:10,885 --> 00:25:15,885
This is why monitoring include model
behavior and downstream operations,

366
00:25:15,935 --> 00:25:17,715
not only infrastructure metrics.

367
00:25:18,215 --> 00:25:23,335
In monitoring, a dashboard should
answer not only is the service

368
00:25:23,335 --> 00:25:27,855
alive, but also is the system
still making good safety decisions?

369
00:25:28,355 --> 00:25:33,985
In many machine learning systems, drift
means that the data distribution changes.

370
00:25:34,255 --> 00:25:37,265
In moderation drift
has additional meaning.

371
00:25:37,925 --> 00:25:40,495
Users are adapting against the system.

372
00:25:40,695 --> 00:25:48,535
Scammers and bad actors actively changing
wording, use coded language, avoid obvious

373
00:25:48,535 --> 00:25:52,335
keywords, and move to indirect behavior.

374
00:25:52,995 --> 00:25:55,575
They are not a passive data distribution.

375
00:25:55,645 --> 00:25:58,115
They are an adversarial population.

376
00:25:58,545 --> 00:26:01,725
The diagram shows several types
of drift around the model.

377
00:26:02,095 --> 00:26:06,885
Language drift means users
change words, slang, or language.

378
00:26:07,275 --> 00:26:11,415
Evasion drift means users learn
how to bypass known checks.

379
00:26:11,855 --> 00:26:16,665
Policy drift means definitions
and enforcement rules change.

380
00:26:17,265 --> 00:26:22,185
Platform or product drift means the
product itself changes: new surfaces, new

381
00:26:22,205 --> 00:26:24,915
communication formats, new user flows.

382
00:26:25,735 --> 00:26:29,875
Reviewer disagreement drift
means reviewers start disagreeing

383
00:26:29,875 --> 00:26:35,045
more often, which may indicate
ambiguous policy or new patterns.

384
00:26:35,495 --> 00:26:41,255
Multimodal and agentic drift means
that risk moves beyond plain text

385
00:26:41,255 --> 00:26:46,365
into images, generated contexts,
tool use, or multi-step actions.

386
00:26:46,865 --> 00:26:54,305
The key sentence for me here is that scam
evolves faster than static benchmarks

387
00:26:54,805 --> 00:26:59,855
The system reduces manual load
while preserving safety coverage

388
00:27:00,355 --> 00:27:01,675
there are three main numbers.

389
00:27:01,755 --> 00:27:06,615
Millions of messages per day, minus
sixty percent reviewer load, and

390
00:27:06,615 --> 00:27:08,515
ninety percent plus violations caught.

391
00:27:09,105 --> 00:27:14,665
But I want to be careful with the, with
impact atric- metrics in moderation.

392
00:27:15,045 --> 00:27:19,035
Big numbers are really attractive,
but they can also be dangerous.

393
00:27:19,415 --> 00:27:23,655
Dashboard can become convincing
before it becomes meaningful.

394
00:27:24,135 --> 00:27:28,515
So the methodology box is very important.

395
00:27:28,735 --> 00:27:34,065
When we say violation caught, we need
to define which policy classes we

396
00:27:34,065 --> 00:27:39,625
mean, what time window we measure,
how borderline cases are counted, and

397
00:27:40,115 --> 00:27:43,295
whether the reviewer denominator changes.

398
00:27:43,795 --> 00:27:49,245
For example reducing reviewer load by
sixty percent is meaning only if we

399
00:27:49,245 --> 00:27:54,115
still preserve safety coverage and don't
simply hide difficult cases from review.

400
00:27:54,655 --> 00:27:59,165
Similarly, ninety percent plus
violations caught might be tied to

401
00:27:59,165 --> 00:28:04,095
specific violation categories and a
clear definition of caught, blocked

402
00:28:04,135 --> 00:28:09,265
automatically, sent to review confirmed
by reviewers, or detected after the fact.

403
00:28:09,885 --> 00:28:12,205
The goal is not to replace reviewers.

404
00:28:12,295 --> 00:28:16,375
The goal is to spend reviewer
attention where it matters most.

405
00:28:16,745 --> 00:28:20,075
So the real impact is not just automation.

406
00:28:20,695 --> 00:28:23,725
It is better allocation
of scarce human judgment.

407
00:28:24,225 --> 00:28:27,155
So let me summarize the main takeaways.

408
00:28:28,155 --> 00:28:29,925
First policy first.

409
00:28:30,425 --> 00:28:35,755
A moderation model can only learn
what the policy defines clearly.

410
00:28:36,115 --> 00:28:41,925
Taxonomy, severity, labeling
rules, and enforcement logic are

411
00:28:41,925 --> 00:28:43,535
part of the model specification.

412
00:28:44,315 --> 00:28:47,015
The second one, hybrid architecture wins.

413
00:28:47,155 --> 00:28:51,835
Rules, machine learning
classifiers, LLMs, and humans solve

414
00:28:51,855 --> 00:28:53,075
different parts of the problem.

415
00:28:53,905 --> 00:28:59,625
The best system is not the one with the
biggest model everywhere, but the one that

416
00:28:59,635 --> 00:29:02,365
uses the right layer for the right risk.

417
00:29:02,865 --> 00:29:04,975
Rare class thinking matters.

418
00:29:04,985 --> 00:29:09,775
Sampling, labeling, metrics, and
thresholds must handle imbalance.

419
00:29:09,845 --> 00:29:11,185
Accuracy is not enough.

420
00:29:11,485 --> 00:29:13,205
Controlled risk is the goal.

421
00:29:13,705 --> 00:29:15,655
The fourth queue design matters.

422
00:29:15,905 --> 00:29:19,595
Reviewer attention is
the scarcest resource.

423
00:29:19,715 --> 00:29:24,575
A good moderation system must prioritize
cases, not just classify messages.

424
00:29:25,205 --> 00:29:27,475
The feedback loop is a product.

425
00:29:27,585 --> 00:29:33,125
Abuse evolves, policies change,
and model quality degrades without

426
00:29:33,295 --> 00:29:35,205
being monitored and retrained.

427
00:29:35,665 --> 00:29:40,515
So the final message is this:
LLM-powered moderation works

428
00:29:40,515 --> 00:29:42,425
when it's designed as a system.

429
00:29:42,705 --> 00:29:47,315
The model is important, but the system
around the model is what makes moderation

430
00:29:47,315 --> 00:29:50,251
safe Scalable and useful in production.

431
00:29:51,211 --> 00:29:51,541
Thank you.

432
00:29:52,041 --> 00:29:57,811
I will be happy to be connected
with you on my LinkedIn page.

433
00:29:58,041 --> 00:29:59,471
So there is a QR.

434
00:30:00,251 --> 00:30:02,151
Thank you for your attention.

435
00:30:02,431 --> 00:30:02,821
See ya.

